  "description": [
    "4 IN AQUEDUCT PATIL A RETIRED NOOK NEAR HIGH BRIDGE WHERE BEAUTIFUL VIEWS AND SOFT DRINKS MAY BE HAD The oldfashioned people who do not ride a wheel and take their exercise by walking often discover picturesque paths and byways which are unknown to the rider One of these is in the northwestefart of the city It is only a short distance from one of the main thoroughfares but it is so thoroughly concealed that its ex istcnce would never be known unless one hap pened to go beyond the ordinary traffic limits The place is known by the name of Aquednct Path It begins at the west end of High Bridge and runs parallel with the river up hill and down dale through rocky cuts and alongside of steep embankments to within a short distance of the viaduct At the beginning of the path in the shadow of the tower and overlooking the river there is a little ivygrown house which shows by its arrangement that people frequent the spot A balcony extends around two sides of the little building and on this tables and chairs are arranged for the accommodation of guests A large oldfashioned icebox occupies a"
